Could you please create a tracking JIRA stating the problem this PR solves?

BTW, are you trying to avoid having multiple builder methods to specify
each thing? The downside of this approach is that the user must always
specify all methods. In the (common) case where all tables have the same
schema, this is harder to use.

Your approach allows for per-table schemas as well, which goes a bit
further than what my PR did. If we do go with this, I believe
getTableSchema needs a way of accessing a list of PCollectionView objects
as well; we've had several user requests for this in batch - a previous
stage calculates the schema based on the entire input PCollection.

R: @jbonofre

Interesting. I think in general, and even closer to BEAM-92, it could look roughly like this then:

```
foos.apply(BigQueryIO.Write.to(
    (foo, window) -> destination,
    (destination) -> new BigQueryIO.Write.Destination(...table name, schema, other options...),
    (foo) -> new TableRow(...))
```

Encapsulating properties of a destination table in a POJO is better than representing them as virtual functions.

This requires that all of these functions, here represented as lambdas, should statically declare and be able to access side inputs. This could be done by shoehorning it into this BigQueryIO.Write.to() API, or could be done by adding an abstraction like SerializableFunctionWithSideInputs or alike.
